PYTHON SMS ENGINE – SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE

Last Updated: 2026-03-25

⸻

OVERVIEW

This system is the SMS Execution Layer of the platform.

It is responsible for:
	•	Communicating with USB GSM modems
	•	Sending SMS via AT commands
	•	Mapping SIMs to modem ports
	•	Returning standardized responses to the SMS Gateway

⸻

ROLE IN OVERALL ARCHITECTURE

Chat App (AI / Logic)
↓
SMS Gateway (Laravel – Control Layer)
↓
Python SMS Engine (Execution Layer) ← THIS SYSTEM
↓
USB Modem (ttyUSB)
↓
SIM Card
↓
Customer Phone

⸻

CORE RESPONSIBILITY

The Python SMS Engine is responsible for:
	•	Hardware-level communication
	•	AT command execution
	•	Modem state handling
	•	SMS transmission

⸻

WHAT THIS SYSTEM DOES
	•	Receives HTTP requests from SMS Gateway
	•	Maps sim_id → ttyUSB port
	•	Sends SMS using AT commands
	•	Handles modem-level errors (timeout, no response, etc.)
	•	Returns normalized response to Gateway
	•	Performs modem health checks

⸻

WHAT THIS SYSTEM DOES NOT DO
	•	No database
	•	No queue system
	•	No retry logic (handled by Gateway)
	•	No business logic
	•	No AI logic
	•	No conversation handling
	•	No customer state

⸻

API ENDPOINTS

POST /send

Receives SMS send request from Gateway.

Input:
	•	sim_id
	•	phone
	•	message
	•	meta (optional)

Output:
	•	success (true/false)
	•	message_id (optional)
	•	error (if failed)
	•	raw response (for debugging)

⸻

GET /health

Returns service status.

⸻

GET /modems/health

Returns modem-level health:
	•	sim_id
	•	ttyUSB port
	•	reachable status
	•	AT response status

⸻

SIM → MODEM MAPPING

Mapping is defined via configuration file.

Example:

{
“12”: “/dev/ttyUSB2”,
“13”: “/dev/ttyUSB5”
}

Rules:
	•	sim_id MUST exist in mapping
	•	No hardcoded ports in code
	•	Mapping is configurable and reloadable

⸻

MODEM COMMUNICATION

Uses AT commands via serial connection.

Basic flow:
	1.	Open serial port
	2.	Send AT → expect OK
	3.	Set SMS mode → AT+CMGF=1
	4.	Send message → AT+CMGS
	5.	Send content + CTRL+Z
	6.	Wait for modem response
	7.	Close connection

⸻

ERROR HANDLING

Errors are normalized into stable codes:
	•	SIM_NOT_MAPPED
	•	PORT_NOT_FOUND
	•	MODEM_OPEN_FAILED
	•	MODEM_TIMEOUT
	•	AT_NOT_RESPONDING
	•	CMGF_FAILED
	•	CMGS_PROMPT_FAILED
	•	SEND_FAILED
	•	UNKNOWN_ERROR

Rules:
	•	Never crash API
	•	Never expose raw stack trace
	•	Always return structured response

⸻

LOGGING

Structured logs are required:
	•	SMS_SEND_ATTEMPT
	•	SMS_SEND_SUCCESS
	•	SMS_SEND_FAILED
	•	MODEM_HEALTH_CHECK

Fields:
	•	sim_id
	•	port
	•	phone
	•	error (if any)

⸻

CONFIGURATION

Environment/config-driven:
	•	SIM mapping file path
	•	Serial timeout
	•	Command timeout
	•	API host/port

Example ENV:
	•	SMS_ENGINE_SIM_MAP_FILE
	•	SMS_ENGINE_SERIAL_TIMEOUT
	•	SMS_ENGINE_COMMAND_TIMEOUT
	•	SMS_ENGINE_HOST
	•	SMS_ENGINE_PORT

⸻

ARCHITECTURE RULES (CRITICAL)
	•	Python engine MUST NOT contain business logic
	•	Python engine MUST NOT store data
	•	Python engine MUST NOT implement retries
	•	Python engine MUST NOT implement queue

⸻

DESIGN PRINCIPLE

Gateway = Control Plane
Python = Execution Plane

⸻

INTEGRATION RULE
	•	Gateway calls Python via HTTP only
	•	No shared memory
	•	No direct modem access from Laravel

⸻

SCALABILITY

This system can be scaled by:
	•	Running multiple Python instances
	•	Each instance handling a set of modems
	•	Gateway routing requests accordingly

